# Vercel Speed Insights Implementation

## Summary
Successfully installed and configured Vercel Speed Insights for the NUMINA Next.js project.

## Changes Made

### 1. Package Installation
- Installed `@vercel/speed-insights` package (version automatically resolved by npm)
- Updated `package.json` with the new dependency
- Generated `package-lock.json` to lock dependency versions

### 2. Code Integration
**Modified: `app/layout.tsx`**
- Added import: `import { SpeedInsights } from '@vercel/speed-insights/next';`
- Integrated `<SpeedInsights />` component at the end of the `<body>` tag
- Placement ensures proper initialization after all page content

## Implementation Details

### Framework-Specific Approach
Following the official Vercel documentation (fetched from https://vercel.com/docs/speed-insights/quickstart), I identified this as a Next.js App Router project and used the appropriate integration method:

1. **Package**: Used `@vercel/speed-insights/next` for Next.js App Router (v13.5+)
2. **Component**: Added `<SpeedInsights />` as a React component
3. **Location**: Placed in the root layout (`app/layout.tsx`) inside the `<body>` tag

### Code Structure Preservation
- Maintained existing code formatting and structure
- Preserved all existing functionality including Nav, footer, and Providers
- Added SpeedInsights as the last element in the body to avoid interfering with existing components

## Build Verification
✅ Build completed successfully with no errors
- Tested with `npm run build`
- All pages generated correctly
- No TypeScript errors introduced
- Warnings related to external dependencies (metamask, walletconnect) were pre-existing

## Next Steps for Deployment
1. **Enable Speed Insights on Vercel Dashboard**: Navigate to your project settings and enable Speed Insights
2. **Deploy to Vercel**: The changes will be active on the next deployment
3. **View Metrics**: After deployment and user traffic, access Speed Insights from the project dashboard

## Files Modified
- `app/layout.tsx` - Added SpeedInsights import and component
- `package.json` - Added @vercel/speed-insights dependency
- `package-lock.json` - Generated lockfile for consistent dependency resolution

## Notes
- The SpeedInsights component is lightweight and has minimal performance impact
- It automatically tracks Core Web Vitals and page load metrics
- Data will appear in the Vercel dashboard after deployment and user interactions
- No additional configuration required - works out of the box for Next.js
